Net Present Value (NPV) is a valuation method used to estimate the present value of a project's cash flows over its useful life. It is calculated by summing all the cash flows of the project and discounting them back to their present value using a specified discount rate. 

The formula for calculating the NPV of a project is:

NPV = ∑(CFt / (1+R)^(n-t))

where:

• CP represents the cash flow at time t;
• R is the discount rate (expressed as a percentage);
• n is the number of years in the project's useful life;
• t is the year in the project's useful life ($t=0$ refers to the present time, $t=1$ refers to the first year, and so on);

For example, let's consider a project with cash flows of $1,000, $1,250, $1,250, $1,000, $500, and $0$ occurring in years 0-5, respectively. A discount rate of 10% has been specified, and the project's useful life is 5 years. The NPV of this project can be calculated as follows:

NPV = (1000 / (1+0.1)^(4)) + (1250 / (1+0.1)^(3)) + (1250 / (1+0.1)^(2)) + (1000 / (1+0.1)^(1)) + (500 / (1+0.1)^(0)) 

NPV = 1,100$\+$1,312.5$\+$1,312.5$\+$1,100 + 500 

NPV = 4,825.00 

Therefore, the NPV of this project would be $4,825.00. If the NPV of a project is greater than zero, it is considered a good investment and should be undertaken. If the NPV is negative, it is a bad investment and should be avoided.
